,"meanings":["Anglicized spelling of Welsh Rhys, in some cases representing a transferred use of the surname so spelled, which is derived from the Welsh given name."]}]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Short form of any of the names beginning with this syllable."],"variants":[{"name":"Alexander","meanings":["From the Latin form of the Greek name <i>Alexandros</i>, from <i>alexein</i> ‘to defend’ + <i>anēr</i> ‘man, warrior’ (genitive <i>andros</i>). The name became extremely popular in the post-classical period, and was borne by several individuals in the New Testament and some early Christian saints. Its use as a common given name throughout Europe, however, derives largely from the fame of  Alexander the Great , King of Macedon (  356–323  bc  ), around whom a large body of popular legend grew up in late antiquity, much of which came to be embodied in the medieval ‘Alexander romances’."]},{"name":"Alan","meanings":["Of Celtic origin and uncertain derivation (possibly a diminutive of a word meaning ‘rock’). It was introduced into England by  Breton  followers of  William the Conqueror , most notably  Alan , Earl of Brittany, who was rewarded for his services with vast estates in the newly conquered kingdom. In Britain the variants  <b>Allan</b>  and  <b>Allen</b>  are considerably less frequent, and generally represent transferred uses of surname forms, whereas in America all three forms of the name are approximately equally common.  See also  Alun ."]},{"name":"Albert","meanings":["From an Old French name, <i>Albert</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to England, displacing the Old English form <i>Æþelbeorht</i>. The name is popular in a variety of forms in Western Europe, and has been traditional in a number of European princely families. It was out of favour in England for centuries, however, and the revival of its popularity in the 19th century was largely in honour of  Queen Victoria's  consort,  Prince Albert of Saxe-Coburg-Gotha ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Rhys ap Rhydderch of Castell Hywel was born about 1160, in Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom, his father, Rhydderch Llwyd ap Cadifor Lord of Castell Hywel, was 38 and his mother, Sioned \"Joan\" Morgan, was -9. He had at least 1 son with Catherine Ddes."},"et":{"ABT    1160–":"umbes 1160–Surnud","1160–Male":"1160–Surnud","1198–Female":"1198–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1238–Male":"1238–Surnud","1230–Male":"1230–Surnud","1235–Male":"1235–Surnud","1242–Male":"1242–Surnud","–Male":"Surnud","1124–Male":"1124–Surnud","1170–Female":"1170–Surnud","ABT    1235":"umbes 1235","ABT    1230":"umbes 1230","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1230":"1230","abt 1230":"umbes 1230","1160":"1160","ABT    1238":"umbes 1238","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","ABT    1160":"umbes 1160","about 1242":"umbes 1242","Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales","of Castell Hywel, Llandysul, Cardiganshire, Wales":"Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales, United Kingdom","of Glyn-Nedd, Glmrgn., Wls.":"Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom","{Cdfr ap Dnwl}":"Ascoli Piceno, Marche, Itaalia","of Castell Hywel,Llandysul,Cardiganshire,Wales":"Llandyssul, Cardiganshire, Wales"},"fi":{"ABT    1160–":"noin 1160–Kuollut","1160–Male":"1160–Kuollut","1198–Female":"1198–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1238–Male":"1238–Kuollut","1230–Male":"1230–Kuollut","1235–Male":"1235–Kuollut","1242–Male":"1242–Kuollut","–Male":"Kuollut","1124–Male":"1124–Kuollut","1170–Female":"1170–Kuollut","ABT    1235":"noin 1235","ABT    1230":"noin 1230","1242":"1242","1198":"1198","1230":"1230","abt 1230":"noin 1230","1160":"1160","ABT    1238":"noin 1238","1170":"1170","1238":"1238","1235":"1235","1124":"1124","ABT    1160":"noin 1160","about 1242":"noin 1242","Llandyssul